        "class": "",
        "text": " to his friend for some third party. What is here censured is the weakness which, for the sake of perhaps worthless companions, lets itself be hampered and endangered by others' obligations. For, as our adage runs, he that is surety for another is never sure himself. The Septuagint takes the \"striking of hands\" to be a sign of joy (Vulgate, ",
